Experiment 3: Creating VPC, EC2 Instances and Application Load Balancer in AWS
Aim

To create a Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), launch EC2 instances in different subnets, configure a web server, and implement load balancing using an Application Load Balancer.

Requirements
AWS Account
Internet connection
Basic knowledge of cloud and networking
Step-by-Step Procedure
1. Create a VPC
Go to AWS Console → VPC Dashboard
Click Create VPC
Select VPC only
Enter:
Name: MyVPC
IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16
Click Create VPC

👉 This creates an isolated network in AWS.

2. Create an Internet Gateway (IGW)
Go to Internet Gateways
Click Create Internet Gateway
Enter name: MyIGW
Click Create
Select the created IGW → Actions → Attach to VPC
Choose MyVPC → Attach

👉 IGW allows communication between VPC and the internet.

3. Create Subnets
Subnet 1
Go to Subnets → Create Subnet
Select MyVPC
Enter:
Name: Subnet-1
Availability Zone: Any (e.g., ap-south-1a)
CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24
Click Create
Subnet 2

Repeat above:

Name: Subnet-2
CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24

👉 Subnets divide the VPC into smaller networks.

4. Create Route Table
Go to Route Tables
Click Create Route Table
Enter:
Name: MyRouteTable
Select VPC: MyVPC
Click Create
5. Associate Subnets with Route Table
Select MyRouteTable
Go to Subnet Associations → Edit
Select:
Subnet-1
Subnet-2
Click Save
6. Add Route to Internet
Go to Routes → Edit Routes
Click Add Route
Enter:
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: Internet Gateway (MyIGW)
Click Save

👉 This allows internet access.

7. Launch EC2 Instances (2 Instances)
Instance 1
Go to EC2 Dashboard → Launch Instance
Configure:
Name: Server-1
AMI: Ubuntu
Instance type: t2.micro
Create/Select Key Pair
Under Network Settings:
VPC: MyVPC
Subnet: Subnet-1
Enable Auto-assign Public IP
Security Group:
Allow HTTP (port 80) from Anywhere
8. Install Apache Web Server

In Advanced Details → User Data, paste:

#!/bin/bash
sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install -y apache2
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

echo "<h1>Server Details</h1><p><strong>Hostname:</strong> $(hostname)</p><p><strong>IP Address:</strong> $(hostname -I | cut -d' ' -f1)</p>" > /var/www/html/index.html

sudo systemctl restart apache2

👉 This installs Apache and displays server details.

Click Launch Instance
Instance 2

Repeat same steps:

Name: Server-2
Subnet: Subnet-2
9. Verify Apache Server
Go to Instances
Copy Public IP
Paste in browser

👉 You should see server details page.

10. Create Target Group
Go to EC2 → Load Balancing → Target Groups
Click Create Target Group
Configure:
Target Type: Instances
Name: MyTargetGroup
Protocol: HTTP
Select VPC: MyVPC
Register Targets:
Select both EC2 instances
Click Create
11. Create Application Load Balancer
Go to Load Balancers
Click Create Load Balancer
Select Application Load Balancer
Configure:
Name: MyALB
Scheme: Internet-facing
IP type: IPv4
Network Mapping:
Select VPC: MyVPC
Select both subnets
12. Configure Security Group
Create new Security Group
Add rule:
Type: HTTP
Source: 0.0.0.0/0
Save
13. Configure Listener
Protocol: HTTP
Forward to: MyTargetGroup

Click Create Load Balancer

14. Test Load Balancer
Copy DNS name of Load Balancer
Paste in browser

👉 Refresh multiple times

Expected Output
You will see responses from:
Server-1
Server-2
IP/Hostname changes on refresh

👉 This shows load balancing is workin
